Dr. Terry Leblanc, Colon and Rectal Surgery

[end section id="20101"]

[start section id="20102"]

Treatment recommendations following resection of a T3, N1 sigmoid colon cancer.
Collaborating provider, Dr. Moses Paik.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Castro is a 84 year-old woman who has slight dementia and resides in a nursing home.  We have been asked by Dr. Leblanc's surgical service to discuss treatment recommendations in the setting of a resected node-positive sigmoid colon cancer.  Mrs. Castro's history is as follows.
1.  She is presently residing in a nursing home due to dementia.  She was found to have melanotic stools and, subsequently, anemia.  Based on that, a colonoscopy was performed on May 26, 2010, which was only able to be advanced to 28 cm.  At that point, a mass was encountered that was not able to transverse.  Biopsies were positive for invasive moderately differentiated grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.
2.  June 14, 2010 - CT chest, abdomen, and pelvis negative for metastatic disease.
3.  June 22, 2010 - Again attempted a repeat colonoscopy.  At this time, was only able to advance to 30 cm.  They were not able to transverse the tumor.
4.  June 24, 2010 - Dr. Leblanc performed a resection of the sigmoid colon.  I do not have a copy of the operative report, however I do have pathology results which is positive for poorly-differentiated grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma noting an ulcerated and polypoid annular mass in the sigmoid colon.  Surgical resected margins are negative.  One of 20 regional lymph nodes positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma (pT3, N1).
Today, Mrs. Castro is one-day postoperative.  She is sitting up in a chair in the Intensive Care Unit, not able to converse partially due to respiratory apparatus.  Daughter is present during this consultation.

[end section id="20103"]

